================================================================================
MBR_PATCH  --  MBR partition table viewer and editor
Part of the mbr88 project: https://github.com/cpiker/mbr88
MIT License  Copyright (c) 2025 Chris Piker
================================================================================

DESCRIPTION

  mbr_patch reads, displays, and interactively edits the 512-byte Master
  Boot Record of an IBM XT-class hard disk image.  It understands the
  standard four-entry MBR partition table and the extended boot menu label
  feature of the mbr88 boot record.

  Changes are always held in memory until you confirm a write with the 'w'
  command.  A backup copy (mbr_file.bak) is written before the file is
  changed.  Pressing 'q' before confirming a write leaves the file and disk
  completely untouched.

================================================================================
USAGE
================================================================================

  mbr_patch  <file>       View partition table and exit (read-only)
  mbr_patch  -p  <file>   Patch an existing MBR interactively
  mbr_patch  -u  <file>   Upgrade existing MBR to mbr88, then edit
  mbr_patch  -n  <file>   Create a new blank mbr88 image, then edit
  mbr_patch  -h           Print a short usage summary

================================================================================
MODES
================================================================================

  (no flag) -- VIEW MODE (read-only)

    Reads the file, checks that it is exactly 512 bytes and has a valid
    55 AA boot signature, prints the partition table, and exits.
    The file is never modified.  Exits with an error if the file does not
    exist, is not 512 bytes, or lacks the 55 AA signature.

  -p -- PATCH MODE

    Validates the file the same way as view mode, then opens an interactive
    session for editing partitions.  If the file contains an mbr88 v0.1
    boot record, boot menu label editing is also available.  A higher mbr88
    version causes a message directing you to get a newer mbr_patch.

  -u -- UPGRADE MODE

    Validates the file, replaces its boot code with the mbr88 v0.1 boot
    record, and preserves the existing partition table entries.  The file
    MUST already exist.  Use -n to create a new image from scratch.
    After the upgrade, the session starts with unsaved changes flagged so
    the 'w' command will immediately offer to write the upgraded boot code.

  -n -- NEW MODE

    Creates a blank mbr88 v0.1 image and opens the interactive session.
    The target file MUST NOT already exist.  The program exits with an
    error if it does, preventing accidental overwrites.

================================================================================
INTERACTIVE COMMANDS
================================================================================

  g   Set drive geometry (heads per cylinder and sectors per track).
      Must be run before 'n'.  IBM XT default: 16 heads, 17 sectors.

  n   Define a new partition or redefine an existing one.
      Requires geometry to have been set with 'g' first.  Prompts for
      starting CHS, ending CHS, partition type, and bootable flag.
      LBA start and size are computed from the CHS values.

  d   Delete a partition slot.  Zeros all 16 bytes of the entry and its
      boot menu label.

  s   Change the partition type byte of an existing entry.

  b   Toggle the bootable flag (0x00=inactive / 0x80=bootable).
      mbr88 does not auto-boot on this flag -- it always shows the menu.
      Any or all partitions may be marked bootable under mbr88.

  l   Set the boot menu label for a partition (mbr88 v0.1 images only).
      Up to 11 characters.  Shown in the boot menu next to the partition
      number.

  p   Print the current partition table.

  t   List common partition type codes.

  w   Show the final table, ask for confirmation, write a backup copy
      to mbr_file.bak, then write the changes to the file.

  h   Print a short command summary.

  q   Quit.  Prompts if there are unsaved changes.

================================================================================
PARTITION TYPE CODES (common values)
================================================================================

  0x00  Empty
  0x01  FAT12
  0x04  FAT16 (less than 32 MB)
  0x05  Extended
  0x06  FAT16B (32 MB or larger)
  0x0B  FAT32
  0x0C  FAT32 LBA
  0x80  MINIX (old)
  0x81  MINIX
  0x82  Linux swap
  0x83  Linux

================================================================================
EXAMPLES
================================================================================

  View the partition table without modifying the file:

    mbr_patch mbr.bin

  Read the live MBR from drive C: into a file and view it:

    fdisk /smbr 1
    ren boot.mbr mbr.bin
    mbr_patch mbr.bin

  Upgrade an existing MBR to mbr88, set labels, and write:

    mbr_patch -u mbr.bin

    At the prompt:
      g    (set geometry -- accept XT default or enter your values)
      l    (set a label, repeat for each partition)
      w    (write the upgraded boot code back to mbr.bin)

  Create a fresh mbr88 image and define partitions:

    mbr_patch -n mbr.bin

    At the prompt:
      g    (set geometry)
      n    (define partition 1, repeat for each partition)
      l    (set labels)
      w    (write the new image to mbr.bin)

  Write the finished image to the hard disk (ELKS/Linux -- CAREFUL):

    dd if=mbr.bin of=/dev/hda bs=512 count=1

================================================================================
MBR88 BOOT RECORD
================================================================================

  mbr88 is a custom MBR for IBM XT-class hardware.  It presents a boot menu
  and always waits for the user to choose what to boot -- it never auto-boots
  a partition on its own.  The menu supports hard disk partitions 1-4 and
  floppy drives A and B.

  The mbr88 boot record retries disk reads up to three times before reporting
  an error, which allows floppy drive motors time to reach stable speed.

  mbr88 is identified by the signature 'mbr88' at MBR offset 0x1B8, followed
  by a version byte at 0x1BD.  Version 0x01 = v0.1.

  Boot menu labels are stored at MBR offset 0x41 in four 16-byte slots.
  Each slot holds up to 11 characters displayed next to the partition number
  in the boot menu.  Labels are only editable on mbr88 v0.1 images.  If a
  newer mbr88 version is found, get an updated mbr_patch from:

    https://github.com/cpiker/mbr88

================================================================================
NOTES
================================================================================

  Drive geometry: IBM XT hard disks typically use 16 heads and 17 sectors
  per track.  The geometry entered with 'g' must match the values used when
  the partitions were originally created, or the computed LBA fields will be
  wrong.  XT-class BIOSes use only the CHS fields and ignore LBA, so wrong
  LBA values rarely cause problems in practice.

  CHS values should be taken from fdisk or the drive's technical
  specification.

================================================================================
FILES
================================================================================

  mbr_file.bak    Backup of the original file, written before any write.

